{
  "text": "The spanwise spacing of the streaks is one of the few universally accepted aspects of boundary-layer structure, where \u03bb + \u2248 100 (here \u03bb + = \u03bbu \u03c4 /\u03bd, \u03bb is the spanwise wavelength, u \u03c4 is the friction velocity given by \u221a \u03c4 w /\u03c1, \u03bd is the fluid kinematic viscosity, \u03c1 is its density, and \u03c4 w is the wall shear stress). In contrast, estimates of the streamwise extent of the streaks varies widely. This is most probably due to the different methods used to make the estimates. The low-speed streaks are seen to extend up to L + x \u2248 2000 in some cases, if the spanwise meandering of the streaks is taken into account. Velocity correlation methods derived from stationary probes would tend to underestimate the streamwise length of a meandering streamwise vortex, as only limited portions of such a meandering vortex would intersect the probe. In addition, as Cantwell points out, even if the low-speed streaks are generated directly by pairs of counter-rotating vortices, it does not necessarily follow that the two must have the same streamwise dimension (see also [CITATION_1] . The persistence distance of the near-wall vortices is difficult to evaluate for the same reasons.",
